segments.text: 10 seconds before it starts recording this is may the 12th and we're looking out on a cloudy sky from the breakfast area i'm chatting with ann rudder erdman we've been acquainted for almost 40 years now and chatting with her about her
experiences here, particularly seeking information about the role, the key role her father played at Texas A&M.
You all moved to College Station in 1958.
And you were getting ready to be what year in school?
It was back to the middle of my sophomore year.
In high school?
In high school.
Describe, as far as you recall, the reactions of the family at moving here.
we weren't real sure what we were getting into.
A&M, I can remember my brother coming to A&M with dad, but none of the three daughters had been here.
And so we really were not, we just weren't sure.
As far as you are able to recall, what did your dad think he was coming to do?
What was his task?
He didn't discuss that with me.
He didn't discuss it.
I know he was very excited about coming.
Now he had been land commissioner, and I know had cleaned up a real first class mess that his predecessor had created.
And he had earned the high regard of Governor Alan Shivers.
Shivers, uh-huh.
All right, now before, your dad was born where?
Eden, Texas.
Eden, and went to high school?
Eden.
and then to Tarleton, JTAC, and then here two years.
And your mom grew up...
In Menard.
In Menard.
Which was the next county to Eden.
And she went to high school...
In Menard.
And then to the University of Texas.
And then to the University of Texas.
Now, I've heard that she was an acquaintance, had friends named Connelly.
She did.
Did she know both?
And Jake Pickle.
She and Jake were really good friends.
The later, the congressman from the Austin area.
Was she acquainted with Nellie?
Yes.
And then your parents meet when?
Most can give you better details.
My dad had an older brother.
And who was about, dad was six years older than mother.
And so I think that the story is that mother first saw dad's picture in an annual.
But then after she finished at Texas, she wound up teaching in Brady where dad was coaching.
So.
Oh, now see, I'm glad you, because I had been told by somebody that they met
when he was teaching and coaching and she was a high school student?
No.
I don't think so.
So what was she teaching?
Well, what would be the least thing you'd ever guess that she would teach?
I don't know.
P.E.
P.E.?
Oh, okay.
And she took P.E., what is the story, something that her brother-in-law was a coach.
And he said she didn't have to take math or a foreign language if she studied PE and it sounded fine.
Right.
Your dad was coaching and he was, what did he teach?
I think they taught everything.
Now this was at what high school?
At Brady High School.
At Brady.
Uh-huh.
And then he goes away to the war, comes back.
He actually goes to Tarleton first.
Oh, that's right.
For Brady, he got appointed.
In fact, I remember one time he said that was...
That was the only job he really worked for.
Oh.
Was to get that coaching job at Tarleton.
Right.
Was he the head coach?
Uh-huh.
In football?
Uh-huh.
And was he doing that when the war started?
Uh-huh.
Oh.
Oh.
All right, and let's see, your memory is not yet there, is it?
No, my brother, two years older, was born in Stephenville while they were at Tarleton.
And then by the time I was born in 1942, I was born at Brooke General, so he was already then in the service.
Okay.
And when your dad comes back from the service, where'd y'all live during the war?
In Braden.
Excuse me, uh-huh, in a little house on South Bridge Street.
with the traffic light in town just outside the window.
And the family consisted during the war of how many children?
Just two.
And that was when we became Bud and Sis because it was James Earl Jr. and my whole name is Margaret Ann.
And that was too long to write on the little, what do they call the letters during the war?
Email.
Was it email?
I started to say that.
It was email.
Female.
Female.
Female.
That's it.
Okay.
Female.
Okay, yeah.
And so my brother at nearly 60 is still Bud Rudder, but I'm not cis anymore.
But you were cis for a while.
Well, in fact, until I left grade when I was 12, and all the family will still call me that.
Oh, I can identify with that, because up in Garland, where I lived until I was 10, my dad was Hack, and I was Hack Jr.,
Oh, really?
To old-timers.
Nobody gives nicknames anymore.
Everybody used to have nicknames.
Okay.
You all move here.
Do you recall your parents' unspoken feelings?
Were they eager?
Glad?
What do you think was there?
I think Mother was a little reluctant because she had longed
to return to Austin, and she was really happy there.
But it really wasn't questioned, it wasn't.
And my dad was one that mother would often say that he doesn't, she would hear things from her friends about goings on on campus before she would hear from him.
So he truly didn't talk about,
Dad would never bring a pencil home from the office.
So the fact that he didn't bring tails or events is really not a surprise.
He very much, the office was office and home was home.
You said you had not been here to visit.
So the first time you come to College Station is when y'all are actually moving?
And you moved into the big, old, Victorian...
Wonderful, wonderful old house.
All right, so you liked it from the first?
Oh, from the very first.
Make believe that I have never seen it.
Describe it for me.
It was two stories.
It had great porches across the front on the first floor and the second floor.
You walk inside and the carpet is deep maroon with a big staircase that goes up and a big grand piano underneath the staircase on the first floor.
There's an elevator.
Apparently one of the previous president's wives was an invalid.

And this little elevator, there of course was not a shaft below the first floor, and the safety regulations were not in place so you could actually, if someone was upstairs coming down, you could open the door on the first floor and stand underneath and it would stop the pressure on your head.
It just was wonderful.
The grounds were beautiful, and it was just across from the chapel, the off-base chapel, and the fountain.
And then to the east of it was Sabisa.
Describe how many rooms down and up.
Oh, there were three parlors, maybe two parlors.
and a fireplace in one of the parlors and a fireplace in the study at the corner.
And the study at the corner is where I spent most of it.
Usually I was studying after everybody went to bed.
And I kind of had it to myself down there in the fire.
There was a huge dining room with a mural on the wallpaper.
And you don't see perhaps how many?
Oh, goodness, I don't know.
I've got pictures of
dinners that I brought girlfriends over, and I mean easily, more than a dozen, yeah, 14, 16.
Kitchen?
Big kitchen, big kitchen, and there were always two people, always black, who were working there on campus.
There would be a gentleman who would do the sweeping and lay the fires and outside things.
Upstairs, how many vendors?
Upstairs, one for my younger brother, a guest room, mother and dad's room, and then it had, there was a seating area off of that where the TV went.
In these days of the TV in every room, that's kind of fun to remember.
And then my two younger sisters shared a room, and then my room was at the very back.
Now was there a basement?
No basement.
But there was a back stairs.
Was an outdoor back stairs?
No.
An indoor back stairs?
Uh-huh.
There were two staircases inside.
An attic?
There was an attic.
I don't remember because that's where the fire started.
Oh, okay.
That's where the fire started because of the mortar and the bricks.
We'll get back to the fire.
And this was the biggest house y'all ever lived in.
Oh, goodness.
I think all of our furniture fit in the upstairs.
Was it fully furnished by the university?
Downstairs it was, and I think even mostly upstairs.
We didn't really have a whole lot.
There were the five kids in our family.
So when y'all arrived, your oldest brother was an A&M student.
Actually, he must have been finishing his last year at Schreiner.
So you're the oldest of the children at home.
Yes.
And you were a high school... Sophomore.
Sophomore.
And it wasn't my car, but mother and dad got a car.
And it was maroon and white, and it was a little Dodge.
And it was one of those that had the gear system that you sort of shifted but you didn't have to.
There's a name for it.
But that way then I could take my brothers, younger brothers and sisters to school.
It was really never considered my car and I didn't take it to the University of Texas.
But it was a car that I drove the kids in.
So you then go to A&M Consolidated, then the high school building on Jersey Street, as we then named it, right across from the campus.
What was it like for you adjusting to a new school?
It was interesting hearing you talk about your son being a junior when you moved to El Paso.
Because I thought when you were telling that, that's just about the age I was.
Now, I moved from a much bigger school in Austin.
here.
I have the best feelings about the memories from then.
Mother and Dad were made so welcome.
I was made so welcome.
Who were some of the people that deserve a note, a pat on the back for working on that welcome?
Well, yeah, as far as Mother and Dad are concerned, the board, of course.
The deans, all of the deans at the time, you know, the
that group of deans and their wives were always wonderful.
At the high school, Mr. Osment was the principal.
That's O-Z-N-E-N-T.
I think it was E-P Osment.
I moved there, I moved there the middle of my sophomore year.
By the end of the year, I'd been elected cheerleader and sophomore favorite.
And I know that this was in part because of mother and dad.
But I just was made, I was absolutely included and made welcome from the very beginning.
And I remember somebody very important to me was Bob Boone, who was the choir director at the time at the high school.
And he said, do you, you know, you've, okay, big deal.
You've gotten yourself here and you've gotten elected.
do you know the name of every student in the high school?
I said, well, of course I don't.
Don't be silly.
He said, until you learn every name, you don't deserve the honor of representing them.
So a lot of, yeah, I've just...
And did anybody ever tease you that you'd come from Austin, from enemy territory or anything?
Sure.
Oh, okay.
And even though I wound up going to the University of Texas, I was never really a flag-waving Longhorn.
And those board members, you said, that welcomed your dad, are there any that you recall that really
were at the top of the list of those who were most cordial, most welcoming?
Oh, not that I can, you know, and I'm not sure that I could recall who was here when Dad first came, or then, you know, then later, you know, people like Mr. Quittenberg.
But he was always very, very respectful of their position in relation to his position.
Now, as I understand it, when he first came,
His title was something like Executive Vice President for a brief time, and then he became President.
Is that as you recall?
So, as far as you recall, when your parents moved, he clearly understood that he was going to be the President.
I just wasn't privy to those conversations.
I just know that, in fact, I've said to my sons, I would wish for you the joy in whatever you choose to do, that you found the joy that my dad had in getting up and going to work every day.
He got up, he walked two blocks down to the Koch building, and whenever he was done, he came home.
I'm not sure what all he did there.
But he did, he did love doing it.
Were you aware, you said he didn't bring office problems home, were you aware as a child at home that his travel schedule sometimes was hectic?
Oh sure, oh sure.
Alright, let's see.
Describe your reaction of being on the campus.
Because you're here two years?
Uh-huh, two and a half.
Two and a half.
Describe your reaction to living on the campus and living in this town.
Well, I just have such fond memories.
I can remember a couple of times.
One time I can remember, just Dad and I were in the car going somewhere.
And I said, you know, there's one thing that really bothers me.
And I said, people have such expectations of me because of you.
And I don't like it.
And he said, well, you know, I understand how that can happen.
And he said, maybe what you need to think about are all the good things.
that have come to our family.
And things you've gotten to do and places you've gotten to be that wouldn't have happened had we not.
And let's see, I think you've mentioned to me before, you did not mind the thought of being a young lady living on the campus where there were all these young men.
Dating was sort of interesting, because I could come in, and back then, you either dated the high school boys or you dated the A&M boys.
You really couldn't date both.
And my dad was very much a believer that if you're in high school, you date high school boys.
And if I would date someone a year or two older who graduated, then I could no longer date him, because he was then an Aggie or whatever, or worse.
So sometimes it'd be kind of funny, like if I was coming in, because you had to park at the side and then walk across the whole front of the house on the porch to get to the front door.
And people would yell.
And I can remember some girlfriends and I decided one weekend that we could sunbathe on the second floor.
And nobody would know.
Well, that wasn't the case either.
We had, I guess, gotten the suntan stuff all over us and stretched out, and the first time we turned over, there was a whole row over across the street watching from the chapel grounds.
There was a university policeman who was always stationed right at the corner of the,
the fountain.
And as I was always running a little late, out of the driveway and around that corner, he would always jump up on the curb.
Do you remember any attempted student pranks around the president's house?
No, no, and by the time some of the serious pranks that you hear about, I was already gone.
No, I really don't.
At that time, we always had the bulldog, and there was a place out by the garage that was a yard for the dog.
When we first came here, girls were still wearing petticoats, adrenaline's.
And I remember the horror of thinking that those were going to have to be hung out to dry in full view.
But as it turned out, even kind of the laundry area was hedged so that it really wasn't in full view.
But those are just some of the things.
And Dad was always, you know, you just didn't step outside unless you were properly dressed or you didn't, you know.
Things like that really were stressed.
Now, could you have a bunch of high school friends over for a Friday night or Saturday night?
Yeah, I could.
They didn't always behave.
I remember having a slumber party, and that was back in the baby doll pajama days, and some of my friends and my girlfriends ran outside to watch the boys march to breakfast.
And I was like,
And let's see, where did you and your high school friends go on a Friday night or a Saturday night for a good time?
Oh, mostly we went to the school library and danced.
And if it wasn't, you know, every ball game we always danced at the library and we decorated that afternoon.
And if we didn't do that, we'd go to each other's houses.
Manning Smith and Nita Smith, their son was in my class, so dancing was a big deal.
I can remember going to the school parking lot, and the cars would all turn their lights on.
We'd turn the music up and dance.
So we did a lot of... Now, did high school kids in your day drink beer?
Very few.
I don't remember ever being around a beer in high school.
Do you remember...
and whiskey was hard to get in this county.
So drunkenness was not a high school problem in those days.
A few of the boys smoked cigarettes.
That was kind of a big deal back then.
And you hadn't even heard the words that we now know about the various drugs.
No.
Let alone, you hadn't seen it.
I remember maybe like after my senior year of high school going to a party and coming in and
And dad was always, he met me at the door downstairs when I came in, and as he was hugging me up the stairs, he was, you've been smoking cigarettes, sister.
And I said, no, dad, I haven't.
He said, somebody has drowned you.
You know, it was, my sisters tell a funny story of even when they got into what we called the new house.
And my sister was a few minutes late and came in and whoever her date was at the night thought he was being funny saying, and he just sort of yelled, said, hey Earl, we're home.
Not knowing that dad, the window was open and dad yells out saying, fine, get her off.
Oh, good, good.
That's a good one.
Now, any of those anecdotes for your life.
Let's see, for you in high school, did you have certain hours you were expected to be in by?
Oh, sure.
Oh, sure.
Well, of course, I went from high school to Littlefield Dorm at the University of Texas, and it was 10 o'clock curfew there, and maybe 12 on the weekends.
I'm sure my curfews were 9.30 or 10, and no dating during the week.
When I first got here, Colonel Davis was here, and his son was two years older, Stedman Davis.
And so Stedman and I kind of chummed up.
We were both on campus.
And I can remember when, just had been here a little while, and I came home from school, and he'd invited me to go get a Coke at Triangle.
And I said, dad, Stephen Davis is downstairs.
And my dad said, what in the hell is he doing here at this time of day?
And by the time I got back downstairs, he wasn't.
He was very strict on who my friends were.
And were your grade reports checked by your parents?
Oh, yes.
That certainly sounds familiar.
They both signed.
Mom signed more than Dad.
I still got them.
But he always checked.
I mean, unless they were all A's, it really wasn't acceptable.
And there was no doubt that you were going to go to college.
Oh, it was never a question.
And the fact that you were female going to college had nothing to do with how important it was that you go.
It wasn't.
You know, I don't know who at 18 really directed toward a profession.
And I remember talking to Dad.
I loved to sew.
I loved home ec courses.
I loved kids.
And so Dad said, well, you know, sister, just...
go ahead and go to education.
And that way, if you'd ever have to have something to fall back on.
The thought of a career really just didn't exist in the late 50s.
As your dad becomes settled into his job,
Who were the key people, as far as you know, that he turned to on the campus for, who were his key subordinates?
Who did he rely upon?
Well, you know about subordinates.
I guess I think about Ed Cooper and Dorsey McCrory.
Yeah, yeah.
Tell me about those people.
You might believe I didn't know anything about them.
And I'm not sure at what point he's, see, they may have even started assisting him after I left.
So.
I just remember, I just remember their dedication.
Yeah, Ed was his assistant.
Uh-huh.
Mm-hmm.
And I just remember him just always being there.
Just...
I don't know that I can tell you anything specific.
We've carried on with the Coopers a lot.
We've flopped babysitters back and forth.
And my kids now babysat their grandkids.
What about Dorsey McClure?
And the same thing.
Ed was so personable and so much fun.
And he was, I don't know.
I'm sure in a lot of respects he was sort of like a son to dad.
Dorsey was more military.
He was less personable.
Had they met during the service, your dad and Dorsey?
I have no idea.
I have no idea.
Because to me, Dorsey was less warm, more businesslike.
Oh, the clerical, the secretary.
Oh, Jerry Haught.
Describe her.
Jerry Haught and Nelda were just wonderful.
Would they have dared...
speak candidly to your dad if they thought he was about to, if the letter didn't say what it should have said?
Dad was very well aware of his limitations in the King's English.
And he very much appreciated how things looked.
Some of the things when I...

Dad was really strict, and he was less strict with the younger kids, but I've always said I love being one of the older ones because my relationship with him as an adult is just something I'd never trade for.
I know he depended on them very much, and they were absolutely dedicated to him.
I don't know what
the formula was, or if it was just in the man.
Do you know whether or not they were, were they there in the office when he?
I don't know.
I don't either.
Because I'm thinking Nelda had to have been a rather young woman at that time.
because this is now 40 years later.
And she's still a young woman.
Did you have any association with Wayne Hall?
You know, I really didn't, and he has shared his writings with Mother.
And she loaned them to me for a couple of days, and I didn't get through them, and she wanted them back.
I want to read what he has written at some point.
Let's go board members.
They were then called board of directors.
They weren't regents yet.
Well, Doc Doherty was one, wasn't he?
We need a list.
We have a list I can tell you better.
Sterling Evans, Zachary, Al Davies, Dick Goodson.
You know, Al Davies had been Dad's roommate.
Oh, I didn't know that.
Yes.
Do you know any anecdotes from that?
When Al Davies' folks brought him to A&M,
they opened the room that was assigned, and it was full of mops and brooms, and they thought surely they had been misdirected because that was obviously the custodial closet.
But I think my dad at that point had the custodial concessions.
Oh, they were lifelong friends.
Because he would end up being the Sears and Roebuck CEO.
And even Mildred, when I came back to Texas in 1970 and...
bought a Sears refrigerator.
She came by to see the babies, and I said, well, you know, I bought a Sears refrigerator.
She said, does it work?
If it doesn't, send it back.
Let's see.
Another one of his classmates was a man named Teague.
Can you share any examples of their relationship?
Oh, gosh.
I think they would have done anything in the world for one another.
And were they close friends as undergraduates?
Yes.
So not only were they classmates, they were friends.
Now Dad was older, because not only did he go to Tarleton for two years before coming here, but I think then he didn't, I think he had to lay out and work a year, too.
So he was an older than average graduate when he left A&M.
Oh, that one, let's digress a second.
about a milk cow.
Tell me your version of that story.
Well, what I hear was that that was part of his stipend, was to bring the milk.
And if the cow didn't provide, then he had to stop by the water fountain on the way to the mess hall.
And that that was when one time when he was short on money and might have to drop out of school,
that the coach came up with that idea.
So I, okay.
When dad left Eden, my father's father, mother said the other day, she said, well, my dad called your dad's dad a commission man.
that he would, had you ever heard that term, a commission man?
And you know, it's sort of like a broker.
And he would broker land, or he would broker.
On a commission.
On a commission.
And when Dad left, when Dad got the scholarship to Tarleton, he had a very good job as a soda jerk at the Eden drug store.
And apparently my grandfather, Rudder, whom I never knew, that he died before Mother and Dad married,
really didn't approve of Dad.
He thought he was making a big mistake leaving that fine job at the drugstore.
To go away.
All right, now, your mother's family already owned the ranch?
